{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"A\n    \n      Spotlight Tour\n      Step-by-step guided tour that dims the page and spotlights each button one at a time. An annotation bubble with a line points to the highlighted control and explains what it does. User clicks \"Next\" to advance. Like Slack's onboarding.\n      \n        ProsFocused attention on one thing at a timeCan't miss any controlGood for first-time users\n        ConsSlow — must click through every stepAnnoying for returning users who just forgot one buttonComplex to implement (positioning, sequencing)","choice":"a","id":null,"timestamp":1775357830140}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"C\n    \n      Grouped Cheat Sheet Panel\n      A slide-out panel or modal listing all controls organized by group (Chapter toolbar, Segment controls, Editing, Track Changes). Each entry shows the icon + label + keyboard shortcut. No visual lines to buttons — just a reference card.\n      \n        ProsClean and organizedEasy to implementGood as a persistent reference\n        ConsDoesn't show WHERE buttons are on screenUsers still have to match icons mentallyLess discoverable / less \"wow\"","choice":"c","id":null,"timestamp":1775357840626}
{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"B\n    \n      Annotated Overlay\n      A single overlay that dims the background and shows ALL annotations simultaneously — each control gets a numbered callout with a line/arrow connecting it to a brief description. Everything visible at once. User presses \"?\" or clicks a help icon to toggle.\n      \n        ProsSee everything at a glanceQuick to dismiss — one key/clickUsers can scan for what they needFeels like a \"cheat sheet\"\n        ConsCan be visually busy with many controlsNeed to carefully position annotations to avoid overlap","choice":"b","id":null,"timestamp":1775357842868}
